        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "As I've been developing this command, I have begun to think this command should just be named `:log`, for the following reasons:\n- This command replaces user commands which are typically named things such as `:LspLog`, `:MasonLog`, etc. Making these commands be a direct naming swap (`:LspLog` to `:log lsp`) is intuitive.\n- `:editlog` takes a lot of characters to type, since `:edit` eats up a lot of the completion. `:log` is much nicer to type.\n- ~~Due to the prevalence of third-party `:FooLog` commands opening a log file in a new tab instead of in the same window, `:editlog` no longer wraps `:edit`, but instead `:tabnew`.~~\n- Unlike `:EditQuery` which wraps `vim.treesitter.query.edit()` and is typically used to edit a file, `:editlog` is meant primarily to view logs. It's more comparable to `:checkhealth`.\n\nI also don't believe we need to reserve the command `:log` for future use. `:log`, if it exists, should be for opening a log file. I don't believe we need an interactive command to write to a log file, and any other uses (trimming a log file, for example) could use a longer name (`:logtrim`, for example).\n\nFor these reasons, I am going to change the PR to rename the command from `:editlog` to `:log`. ",
